## 6. Platform Overrides

Platform-specific overrides are defined in `native-test-groups.json` under `platformOverrides`:

```json
{
  "E": {
    "name": "mobile-specific",
    "platformOverrides": {
      "android": {
        "skip": ["swipe-back.yaml"]
      }
    }
  }
}
```

**Current overrides:**

| Platform | Group | Skipped Flow | Reason |
|---|---|---|---|
| Android | E (mobile-specific) | `swipe-back.yaml` | Android uses system back button, not iOS swipe-back gesture |

The runner automatically filters skipped flows per-platform before execution.

---

## 7. Parallel Execution & Concurrency Locks

Native and Playwright E2E runners use **separate lock files** to prevent multiple instances of the same runner type while allowing cross-runner parallelism:

| Runner | Lock File | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| Playwright (web) | `/tmp/e2e-runner.lock` | Prevents concurrent Playwright runs |
| Maestro (native) | `/tmp/maestro-e2e-runner.lock` | Prevents concurrent Maestro runs |

**Why separate locks:** Both runners share the same fixture data namespace on the backend. Two Maestro runners would corrupt each other's fixture state. But Playwright (web) and Maestro (native) can run in parallel because they exercise different build artifacts against the same backend.

Lock files store the PID of the running process. Stale locks (dead PID) are automatically cleaned up.

